    summary:
      "The book of Judges opens with a question that sounds hopeful — 'Who shall go up first for us against the Canaanites?' — but the answer unravels almost immediately. Judah goes up and wins battles, but the victories are partial. Tribe after tribe fails to drive out the inhabitants of the land. The refrain 'did not drive out' repeats like a drumbeat: Manasseh didn't, Ephraim didn't, Zebulun didn't, Asher didn't, Naphtali didn't, Dan was pushed back entirely. What was supposed to be a conquest narrative becomes a catalog of compromise.\n\nThe angel of the LORD appears at Bochim — the name means 'weepers' — and delivers the verdict: because Israel broke the covenant, God will no longer drive out the nations before them. These peoples will become thorns in their sides, and their gods will become a snare. The people weep, but the text doesn't tell us they change.\n\nThis is the hinge of the entire book. Everything that follows — every cycle of oppression and deliverance, every increasingly brutal judge — grows from this soil of incomplete obedience. The conquests that looked close enough turn out to be the seeds of catastrophe.",
