      "The opening chapter establishes the theology of the entire book: partial obedience is functional disobedience. Israel's failure isn't dramatic rebellion; it's the slow erosion of following through. The Canaanites they tolerate become the Canaanites who dominate them. The gods they permit become the gods they worship.\n\nThis passage also introduces a critical idea about divine response. God doesn't simply punish; God withdraws assistance. The consequences are organic, not arbitrary — you chose to live alongside these nations, so now you'll discover what that actually costs.",
    relationalNote:
      "The relationship between Israel and the land is the unspoken protagonist of this passage. In the biblical imagination, the land isn't real estate — it's covenant gift, and how you treat it reflects how you treat the Giver. When Israel settles for coexistence with the peoples they were told to dispossess, they're not being tolerant in any modern sense. They're hedging their bets, keeping one foot in the old world while claiming to stand in the new one. The weeping at Bochim is the sound of people who realize too late that half-measures have full consequences.",
    conceptualNote:
      "The theology of 'the snare' — that what you tolerate eventually masters you — runs through the entire Deuteronomistic history. It's not unique to Judges, but Judges makes it visceral. The incomplete conquest also raises hard questions about divine commands and moral agency that the text doesn't resolve neatly. What it does make clear is the narrative logic: Israel's later suffering is connected to these early compromises not as arbitrary punishment but as cause and effect. The thorns you refuse to clear become the thorns you live among.",
    climateNote:
      "The geography of incomplete conquest maps almost exactly onto the most fertile and strategically valuable parts of Canaan. The plains — where the Canaanites had iron chariots — were the agricultural heartland. The hill country was harder to farm but easier to defend. Israel's failure to take the lowlands wasn't just military timidity; it reflected a practical calculation about what was worth fighting for. The irony is that the 'easier' path of accommodation in the valleys led to centuries of cultural and religious assimilation that proved far more costly than any battle would have been.",
