    summary:
      "This passage is the interpretive key to the entire book. After Joshua's generation dies, a new generation arises 'who did not know the LORD or the work that he had done for Israel.' The text lays out a pattern that will repeat with devastating regularity: Israel abandons Yahweh, serves the Baals, provokes divine anger, is handed over to oppressors, cries out in distress, and God raises up a judge to deliver them. Then the judge dies, and the cycle begins again — only worse.\n\nThe narrator is explicit that this isn't a circle but a downward spiral. Each generation sinks lower than the one before. 'They did not drop any of their practices or their stubborn ways.' The judges themselves deteriorate — from the faithful Othniel to the compromised Samson, from leaders who unite the tribes to leaders who can barely manage their own households.\n\nGod's response is complex and worth sitting with. The text says God was 'moved to pity by their groaning' but also that God left nations in the land specifically to test Israel. Compassion and consequence exist simultaneously. The God of Judges is not indifferent, but neither is God willing to override human agency indefinitely.",
