      "The Baal worship that the text condemns wasn't random idolatry — it was practical agriculture. Baal was the storm god, the rain-bringer. For subsistence farmers in a land without reliable irrigation, worshipping Baal was an insurance policy. You prayed to Yahweh for covenant faithfulness, but you hedged your bets with Baal for the harvest. The temptation wasn't exotic or obviously evil; it was the entirely rational calculation of people who needed rain to survive. Understanding this makes the cycle less about stupidity and more about the daily pressure of choosing faith over pragmatism.",
    modernParallel:
      "The Judges cycle is uncomfortably familiar to anyone who's ever made a New Year's resolution. You hit bottom, you cry out for change, something shifts, you feel better — and then you slowly drift back to exactly where you were. The addiction counselor sees it. The therapist sees it. The pastor sees it. The person living it usually doesn't see it until they're back at the bottom again.\n\nBut the passage isn't just about individual habit loops. It's about institutional and cultural memory. 'A generation arose who did not know the LORD' could describe any community that assumed its values would transmit themselves. Churches that stopped teaching doctrine and wondered why their kids left. Democracies that stopped teaching civics and wondered why their citizens lost faith in institutions. Families that assumed love was obvious and never said it out loud.\n\nThe spiral, not the circle, is the key. Each turn gets worse because the infrastructure of recovery degrades. The first time you break a promise, the relationship can absorb it. The fifteenth time, there's no trust left to draw on. Judges is honest about what happens when a society exhausts its moral capital.",
